AB  - The message conveyed in this chapter is that economic development depends on and may be limited by ecosystem life support. Through case studies of fisheries and aquaculture in Scandinavia, we illustrate that there is a strong complementarity between these human activities and the life-supporting environment, and argue that the life support environment is the precondition for their socio-economic development. The quantitative estimates reveal that Baltic fisheries and Norwegian fish farming are dependent on large ecosystem support areas, and that coastal seas put constraints on the possibilities to physically expand fisheries and aquaculture. In all of the studies reviewed the biophysical support from coastal seas is estimated to be at least twice as high as the total biophysical support from society required to sustain fisheries and aquaculture. The results are discussed in relation to basic ecological economic principles, conventional exploitative development, limits to scale and sustainability issues. We suggest that fisheries and aquaculture management would benefit from combining experiences gained in local-level community-based resource management with principles of ecological engineering.
